The key information supporting the identification of the type of bone in the inter-radicular area comes primarily from understanding the structure and classification of bones. According to the articles reviewed, both cortical and trabecular (also referred to as cancellous) bones exist. Given that the inter-radicular area typically refers to spaces located among tooth roots, it would predominantly contain trabecular/cancellous bone rather than dense cortical bone due to its porous and supportive role facilitating blood vessel entry and nutrient diffusion.
Therefore, my answer is \boxed{B}. Based on anatomical considerations and the context-specific functions of the inter-radicular areas, they house cancellous/bone marrow-rich regions essential for root support and vascular perfusion, thus aligning them more closely with B: Cancellous.
\boxed{B}
